			<h3 ><a href="#p138306">Re: 次第 / たび（に） / ～たとたん（に） / か～ないかのうちに</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=138306&amp;sid=67fd23a779cc7131461e20379bbac4d9#p138306"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=25932&amp;sid=67fd23a779cc7131461e20379bbac4d9">Hyperworm</a></strong> &raquo; Fri 10.10.2008 11:06 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">Thanks very much for the detailed posts, cocoさん, I have a pretty good understanding of these structures now... in theory <img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /> <br /><br />It seems to me that a rough English analogue for 「～かしないかのうちに」 would be &quot;before one could even tell whether or not [he/she/they] ～&quot;. Or &quot;before [I] had even figured out whether or not [he/she/they] ～&quot;.<br /><br />(The above not intended to act as a replacement for detailed explanations, but as a memory jogger for them.)</div>

